rs at the scene of the riots? If there were, were they detained, warned, or deported? -- t95. How do religious leaders and the residents of Lhasa view these riots since September 1987? -- t96. Why were foreigners not allowed to travel nor foreign reporters permitted to cover news in Tibet during riots? -- t97. After the riots in Lhasa, were any leaders of the Tibet Autonomous Region dismissed or promoted? Are more soldiers or policemen to be sent to Tibet? -- t98. What countermeasures have the Tibetan authorities taken since the riots? Are the masses allowed to hold parades and demonstrations? -- t99. What is the situation in Tibet now? -- t100. Some foreign newspapers said recently that the Tibet authorities have dispatched people to temples and monasteries to throw out those lamas and nuns who participated in the riots. Is this true? -- tA Comparative Chronology of Tibet and China -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe land of Tibet—its people, culture, and religion—has long been both an object of contention and a source of fascination. Since 1959, Tibet has also been at the center of controversy when China's "peaceful liberation" of the land of snows led to the Lhasa uprising and the Dalai Lama's escape to India. Authenticating Tibet: Answers to China's "100 Questions" offers clear and unbiased responses to a booklet published by the Chinese government in 1989, which sought to counter the criticism generated by the Dalai Lama and his followers and offer the PRC's "truth" about Tibet and Tibetans. In Authenticating Tibet, international Tibet scholars provide historically accurate answers to 100 Questions and deal evenhandedly with both China's "truth" about Tibet and that of the Dalai Lama and his followers. Designed for use by a general audience, the book is an accessible reference, free of the polemics that commonly surround the Tibet question. Although these experts refute many of the points asserted by China, they do not offer blanket endorsements for the claims made by the pro-Tibet movement. Instead, they provide an accurate, historically based assessment of Tibet's past and its troubled present.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsia. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aBarnett, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlondeau, Anne-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlondeau, Anne-Marie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuffetrille, Katia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuffetrille, Katia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChayet, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodin, Thierry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Andrew M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyatso, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarmay, Samten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKvaerne, Per, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopez, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopez, Donald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeyer, Fernand, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanglung, Jampa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShakya, Tsering, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSperling, Elliot, ec